05593nam a22007455i 9781487595814DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191978onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875958147 a10.3138/97814875958142doi  a(DE-B1597)513680  a(OCoLC)1091660149  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aHIS0520002bisacsh00aEuropean Settlement and Development in North America /ced. by James R. Gibson. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©1978  a1 online resource (242 p.) :bfigs, tables, maps, hts throughout  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tEditor's foreword -- tContents -- tPrologue: Andrew Hill Clark, historical geographer -- tThe extension of France into rural Canada -- tOld Russia in the New World: adversaries and adversities in Russian America -- tThe formation of early American cultural regions: an interpretation -- tAntebellum tidewater rice culture in South Carolina and Georgia -- tThe Hudson's Bay Company fur trade in the eighteenth century: a comparative economic study -- tTerritory and ethnic identity: some new measures of an old theme in the cultural geography of the United States -- tThe early Victorian city in England and America: on the parallel development of an urban image -- tThe weakness of place and community in early Pennsylvania -- tEpilogue -- tAndrew Hill Clark and his work -- tContributors -- tSubscribers0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAndrew Hill Clark (1911-1975) was responsible for much of the recent rise of historical geography in North America. The focus on his research was the opening of New World lands by European peoples, and this North American experience is the subject of this collection of essays written by eight of Clark's students. They examine the role of a new physical and economic environment – particularly abundant and cheap land – in the settlement of New France, the cultural and physical problems that conditioned Russian America, the transformation of cultural regionalism in the eastern United States between the late colonial seaboard and the early republican interior, the changing economic geography of rice farming on the antebellum Southern seaboard, the interrelationships of the European and Indian economies in the pre-conquest fur trade of Canada, differential acculturation and ethnic territoriality among three immigrant groups in Kansas in the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, the development in England and the United States of similar social geographic images of the Victorian city, and the erosion of a sense of place and community by possessive individualism in eighteenth-century Pennsylvania. The essays are preceded by an appreciation of Clark as an historical geographer written by D.W. Meinig and are brought together in an epilogue by John Warkentin. The work is an unusually consistent Festchrift which should appeal to all interested in the patterns of North American settlement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / Historical Geography.2bisacsh1 aCole Harris, R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibson, James R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibson, James R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHilliard, Sam B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLemon, James T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcquillan, D. Aidan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeinig, D. W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitchell, Robert D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary